[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 214. This includes 19 countries (including 4 territories) from the Western Pacific region, 61 countries (including 7 territories) from the European region, 10 countries from the South East Asia region, 22 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 54 countries (including 19 territories) from the Americas region, and 48 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:
------------------------------------------
The Americas region reported 43 300 new cases (49.4% of the global newly reported cases), and 3126 deaths (57.6%) were recorded for this 24-hour period. Of the newly confirmed cases in the region, 51.1% were reported by the USA, followed by Brazil at 24.3%, and Peru at 8.4%. Recognizing that USA data are overshadowing the regional proportions, if newly confirmed cases from the USA are excluded, then Brazil reported 49.6% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Peru at 17.1%, Mexico at 7.6%, and Chile at 7.2%.

The European region reported 28 308 new cases (32.3% of the global newly reported cases) and 1941 deaths (35.8%). Russia reported 37.8% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, the UK 19.5%, Turkey 7.0%, Italy 4.9%, Germany 4.3%, and Spain 4.0%.

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 8125 new cases (9.3% of the global newly reported cases) and 143 deaths (2.6%). Saudi Arabia reported 22.1% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Pakistan at 21.7%, Iran at 18.3%, Qatar 11.3%, and the United Arab Emirates at 6.2%.

The African region reported 2247 new cases (2.6% of the global newly reported cases) and 47 deaths (0.87%). South Africa reported 18.9% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Nigeria at 17.0%, Ghana at 16.6%, Algeria at 8.2%, Mayotte at 5.1%, Gabon at 4.8% at 6.2%, and the DR Congo 4.5%.

The Western Pacific region reported 1263 new cases (1.4% of the global newly reported cases) and 33 deaths (0.61%). Singapore reported 58.7% of the newly reported cases, followed by the Philippines at 26.8%, and Japan at 6.7%. Removing Singapore from the denominator has the Philippines at 64.9%, Japan at 16.1%, Malaysia at 7.5%, and Australia at 4.0%.

The South East Asia region reported 4486 new cases (5.1% of the global newly reported cases) and 139 deaths (2.6%). India reported 75.6% of newly reported cases, followed by Bangladesh at 15.7% and Indonesia at 7.5%. Removing India from the denominator, Bangladesh represents 64.4% of the newly reported cases, Indonesia represents 30.8%, the Maldives at 2.7%, and Myanmar at 1.3%.

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 8 May 2020, at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. One sees the contribution of the ongoing epidemics in Europe and the increasing cases in the Americas region, fueled by the USA, but other countries are following suit. The curve tends to drop over the weekends and rebounds following the weekend. Europe has not been rebounding as high at the end of the weekend, demonstrating decreasing newly confirmed cases. South East Asia has been gradually increasing as the cases continue increasing in India.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: It is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time we've accessed the Johns Hopkin's CSSE or Worldometer website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have, at times, significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the John Hopkins CSSE or Worldometer table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4). - Mod.MPP]
